Week 2 
linux all commmand

`pwd`
Shows the current working directory.

`ls`
Lists files and directories.

`ls -l`
Lists files with detailed information.

`ls -a`
Shows all files, including hidden files.

`cd directory_name`
Changes the current directory.

`cd ..`
Moves one directory back.

`touch filename`
Creates a new empty file.

`mkdir directory_name`
Creates a new directory.

`cp source destination`
Copies a file from one location to another.

`cp -r source_directory destination`
Copies a directory and all its contents.

`mv source destination`
Moves or renames a file or directory.

`rm filename`
Removes a file.

`rm -r directory`
Removes a directory and all its contents.

`rm -rf directory`
Forcefully removes a directory and everything inside it.

`rmdir directory`
Removes an empty directory.

`cat filename`
Displays the contents of a file.

`echo "text" > filename`
Writes text into a file (overwrites existing content).

`echo "text" >> filename`
Appends text to the end of a file.

`ln source hardlink`
Creates a hard link.

`ln -s source softlink`
Creates a symbolic (soft) link.

`df`
Displays disk space usage.

`df -h`
Displays disk space in human-readable format (KB, MB, GB).

`free`
Displays RAM and swap memory usage.

`free -h`
Displays memory usage in human-readable format.

 `vmstat`
Displays virtual memory and system performance statistics.

 `vmstat -a`
Displays active and inactive memory statistics.

 `ps -ef`
Displays all running processes with detailed information.

 `kill PID`
Gracefully terminates a running process.

 `kill -9 PID`
Forcefully terminates a running process (SIGKILL).

 `ssh -i "key.pem" username@public-ip`
Connects securely to a remote Linux server using SSH.

FILE PERMISSION 
 `chmod 400 key.pem`
Changes the key file permission to read-only for the owner.

USER COMMANDS
 `sudo adduser username`
Creates a new user.

 `sudo passwd username`
Sets or changes the password of a user.

 `su username`
Switches to another user.

 `su - username`
Switches to another user and loads their login environment.

 `exit`
Returns to the previous user or exits the current shell.

 `whoami`
Displays the current logged-in user.

 `id username`
Displays the UID, GID, and groups of a user.

 `groups`
Displays the groups of the current user.

 `sudo groupadd groupname`
Creates a new group.

 `sudo groupdel groupname`
Deletes a group.

 `sudo usermod -aG groupname username`
Adds a user to a secondary group.

 `sudo gpasswd -d username groupname`
Removes a user from a group.

 `sudo userdel username`
Deletes a user account.

 `sudo userdel -r username`
Deletes a user account along with its home directory.

sudo apt -get packagename
Downloads files from the Internet.

`apt update`
Updates the package list (Ubuntu).

`apt upgrade`
Upgrades installed packages.

`apt install package`
Installs a package.

`apt remove package_name`
Removes a package.

